name: ben galor
description: Some of the other factors that drive Safer City projects are: a strong city economy, level of safety and security threat, availability of internet protocol, susceptibility to natural disasters, improved private and public partnership, and so on. ‘Safer City’ concept is expected to witness significant traction over the next few years as external/internal threat factors are given more importance by governments across the world. The higher the internal/external threat of terrorist attacks, the more probability there is of a city implementing a safer city project. In terms of adoption, the North American market has already seen some rapid progress after the 9/11 attacks. New York City is one of the most “surveilled” cities in the world with video surveillance cameras located at almost every junction, intersection, building, and public area in the city. Other major cities such as Tokyo, Los Angeles, and so on, are on the forefront in adopting safer city projects and related technologies. As critical assets in a city’s infrastructure, security technologies and solutions in future cities will play an important role in promoting better well-being and will support city operators to better cope with security and safety challenges. In the next 5-10 years, Frost & Sullivan expects safer city projects to become integral part of a city’s development schemes proposed by the respective governmen

description: Towards the end of my tenure at SAIC, I served as the Program Manager for the SAIC-led IPT of the Distributed Common Ground Station – Army (DCGS-A) v4 effort; a joint initiative between SAIC and other industry partners such as Northrop Grumman, General Dynamics and Lockheed Martin. I was responsible for all aspects of the program including PnL; managing the cost, schedule, performance and staffing needs for a challenging effort with incremental funding to bring the US Army closer to its Net-Centric Future Combat Systems (FCS) requirements for the 21st century battlefield. I regularly briefed Business Unit level management as well as the US Army's Product Managerial Staff (O-6 & O-5 level officers) for DCGS-A v4. Typical with any PM role I managed and tracked earned value across a portfolio of projects geared towards Command and Control; ensuring the Government understood the general health and well being of its acquisition investment. Prior to the DCGS-A v4 work, I oversaw the Joint Intelligence Operational Capability - Iraq (or JIOC-I also known as DCGS-A v2) for US Army INSCOM. In that position I managed cost, schedule, performance and staffing of internationally deployed assets (both human and material) for this $110M+ program. I worked closely with project control, regularly producing financial forecasts that had visibility to the highest levels of the Army. Earlier in my career with SAIC I operated chiefly as a Senior Software & Systems Engineer as well a Technical Project Manager (TPM). As the TPM, I managed an initiative called the Enablement Strategy (ES); a program which was the implementation arm of a board of governance known as the Intelligence Community Metadata Working Group (IC MWG now the IC DMB), funded by the Director of National Intelligence CIO's Office; the direct result of a Presidential Executive Order to facilitate better data sharing and collaboration across IC enclaves to support the War On Terror.
